= 2008–2009 | nationalteam3 = [[France national under-18 football team|France U18]] | nationalcaps3 = 5 | nationalgoals3 = 0 | nationalyears4 = 2009–2010 | nationalteam4 = [[France national under-19 football team|France U19]] | nationalcaps4 = 4 | nationalgoals4 = 1 | nationalyears5 = 2011 | nationalteam5 = [[France national under-20 football team|France U20]] | nationalcaps5 = 5 | nationalgoals5 = 0 | club-update = 16:19, 27 October 2018 (UTC) | ntupdate = 18 October 2013 }} '''Loïc Damour''' (born 8 January 1991) is a French professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]].
==Club career== Loïc began his career with his local club US Chantilly before moving to the famous [[INF Clairefontaine|Clairefontaine academy]] in 2004. While training at Clairefontaine, he also attended the prestigious sports club [[Athletic Club de Boulogne Billencourt]], which also trained current French stars [[Hatem Ben Arfa]] and [[Issiar Dia]]. After leaving Clairefontaine, he joined [[RC Strasbourg]].
In April 2008, Loïc signed his first professional contract agreeing to a three-year deal keeping him with Strasbourg until 2011.<ref>[http://strasbourg.football.fr/2008/04/24/2116-deux-nouveaux-jeunes-passent-pros Deux nouveaux jeunes passeront pros] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080621105229/http://strasbourg.football.fr/2008/04/24/2116-deux-nouveaux-jeunes-passent-pros |date=2008-06-21 }}</ref> After spending one year in the [[Championnat de France Amateurs|reserves]], he was promoted to the senior squad and was assigned the 26 shirt. He made his professional football debut for Strasbourg on 4 August 2008 in a [[Ligue 2]] match against [[Montpellier HSC|Montpellier]] coming on as a substitute.<ref>[http://www.lfp.fr/ligue2/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008/2009&code_evt=D2&code_jr_tr=J01&num_ordre=8] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907054836/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue2/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008%2F2009&code_evt=D2&code_jr_tr=J01&num_ordre=8 |date=2008-09-07 }}</ref>
On 26 October 2009, Damour signed a contract extension with Strasbourg until the year 2013.<ref>[http://www.mercato365.com/ligue-2/article_357155_Strasbourg-Damour-jusqu-en-2013.shtml Damour jusqu'en 2013]</ref>
On 6 July 2017, following the expiry of his contract with [[Football Bourg-en-Bresse Péronnas 01|Bourge-Péronnas]], Loïc Damour signed for [[EFL Championship]] side [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] on a free transfer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/cardiff-city-sign-french-midfielder-13292802 |title=Cardiff City sign French midfielder Loïc Damour on a free transfer |publisher=WalesOnline |author=Ian Mitchelmore |date=6 July 2017 |accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref> He made his debut for the club on the opening day of the 2017–18 season during a 1–0 victory over [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]], as a substitute in place of [[Lee Tomlin]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40760771 |title=Burton Albion 0–1 Cardiff City |publisher=BBC Sport |date=5 August 2017 |accessdate=5 August 2017}}</ref>
==International career== Damour is a France youth international having played for the [[France national under-16 football team|U-16s]], [[France national under-17 football team|U-17s]], and the [[France national under-18 football team|under-18 team]]. He also played with the [[France national under-19 football team|France U-19]] squad, till 2011. He was captain of the U-16 squad and was a part of the U-17 squad that finished runners-up at the [[2008 UEFA European Under-17 Football Championship]].
